Introduction and Background¶

Tobacco Usage and Disability Prevalence by Jackson Scrimpshire and Nikhil Modayur. The GitHub repository can be found here. The live site can be found here

Description of Project:

This project will seek to understand questions related to the DHDS database collected by the CDC, and assess possible correlations with other public health datasets including tobacco usage. Possible questions that will be investigated include:

  • What geographic regions have the highest percentage of disabilities?

  • What disability types are most common? Does the presence of one disability type increase the likelihood of others?

  • How does tobacco usage correlate with disability status? Different disability categories?

Datasources:

  1. DHDS - Prevalence of Disability Status and Types. Disability and Health Data System (DHDS) is an online source of state-level data on adults with disabilities. Users can access information on six functional disability types: cognitive (serious difficulty concentrating, remembering or making decisions), hearing (serious difficulty hearing or deaf), mobility (serious difficulty walking or climbing stairs), vision (serious difficulty seeing), self-care (difficulty dressing or bathing) and independent living (difficulty doing errands alone).
  2. BRFSS Prevalence and Trends Data: Tobacco Use - Four Level Smoking Data for 1995-2010

Collaboration Plan: We have a shared Google Colab and GitHub where we will push our code to each other. We will also coordinate via text messages and in person meetings when needed. At minimum, we will touch base regarding the project once a week.

Project Goals:

  1. Create a regression model that will predict the smoking values in future years

  2. Quantify relationships between disability status and smoking prevalence through hypothesis testing and regression models.

  3. Create interactive visualizations of disability prevalence and tobacco usage across states

All the columns with only one unique value can be dropped. Let's see how this dataset appears with only columns with relevant information. Data val and data val alt are also copies, and have the same information.

In [ ]:
# Print original shape
print(f"Original shape: {dhds.shape}")

# Drop unnecessary columns
columns_to_drop = [
    "DataSource",               # Always 'BRFSS'
    "Category",                 # Always 'Disability Estimates'
    "Indicator",                # Always 'Disability status and types among adults 18 years of age or older'
    "Data_Value_Unit",          # Always '%'
    "Data_Value_Type",          # Always 'Age-adjusted Prevalence'
    "StratificationCategory1",  # Always 'Overall'
    "Stratification1",          # Always 'Overall'
    "CategoryID",               # Always 'DISEST'
    "IndicatorID",              # Always 'STATTYPE'
    "LocationID",               # Already have state
    "DataValueTypeID",          # Always 'AGEADJPREV'
    "StratificationCategoryID1",# Always 'CAT1'
    "StratificationID1",        # Always 'BO1'

    # Redundant columns
    "Data_Value_Alt",           # Same as Data_Value

    # ID columns with no analytical value
    "ResponseID",               # Encodes the same info as 'Response'

    # Sparse columns
    "Data_Value_Footnote_Symbol", # Mostly NaN with some '*'
    "Data_Value_Footnote",        # Mostly NaN with some 'Data suppressed'
    "StratificationCategory2",    # Not in unique values list, likely sparse
    "Stratification2",            # Not in unique values list, likely sparse
    "StratificationCategoryID2",  # Not in unique values list, likely sparse
    "StratificationID2"           # Not in unique values list, likely sparse
]

# Check if all columns exist
columns_to_drop = [col for col in columns_to_drop if col in dhds.columns]
dhds_clean = dhds.drop(columns=columns_to_drop)

# Keep LocationDesc for reference but create a state-name mapping dictionary
state_names = dict(zip(dhds['LocationAbbr'], dhds['LocationDesc']))

# Then drop LocationDesc
if 'LocationDesc' in dhds_clean.columns:
    dhds_clean = dhds_clean.drop(columns=['LocationDesc'])

# Convert data types
dhds_clean['Year'] = dhds_clean['Year'].astype(int)
dhds_clean['Data_Value'] = dhds_clean['Data_Value'].astype(float)
dhds_clean['Low_Confidence_Limit'] = dhds_clean['Low_Confidence_Limit'].astype(float)
dhds_clean['High_Confidence_Limit'] = dhds_clean['High_Confidence_Limit'].astype(float)
dhds_clean['Number'] = dhds_clean['Number'].astype(float)
dhds_clean['WeightedNumber'] = dhds_clean['WeightedNumber'].astype(float)

# Rename columns for clarity
column_rename = {
    'LocationAbbr': 'state',
    'Response': 'disability_type',
    'Data_Value': 'prevalence_pct',
    'Low_Confidence_Limit': 'ci_lower',
    'High_Confidence_Limit': 'ci_upper',
    'Number': 'sample_size',
    'WeightedNumber': 'population_estimate'
}

dhds_clean = dhds_clean.rename(columns=column_rename)

# Create a new column for simplified disability category
dhds_clean['disability_category'] = dhds_clean['disability_type'].str.replace(' Disability', '')

# Handle special case for 'No Disability'
dhds_clean['disability_category'] = dhds_clean['disability_category'].replace('No', 'None')

# Check for any remaining missing values
missing_values = dhds_clean.isnull().sum()
print(f"Columns with missing values:\n{missing_values[missing_values > 0]}")

# Calculate confidence interval width (uncertainty measure)
dhds_clean['ci_width'] = dhds_clean['ci_upper'] - dhds_clean['ci_lower']

# Add a flag for data quality (wider CI = less reliable)
dhds_clean['low_reliability'] = dhds_clean['ci_width'] > 5  # Flag CIs wider than 5 percentage points

# Display cleaned dataset info
print(f"Cleaned shape: {dhds_clean.shape}")
print(f"Columns in cleaned dataset: {list(dhds_clean.columns)}")

# Display first few rows of cleaned dataset
print("\nSample of cleaned dataset:")
print(dhds_clean.head())

# Save cleaned dataset
dhds_clean.to_csv('dhds_clean.csv', index=False)
print("\nCleaned dataset saved to 'dhds_clean.csv'")

# Basic summary statistics
print("\nSummary statistics for prevalence percentages:")
print(dhds_clean.groupby('disability_category')['prevalence_pct'].describe())

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))

# Filter out the 'None' category
disability_data = dhds_clean[dhds_clean['disability_category'] != 'None']

# Create a custom order with 'Any' first
category_order = ['Any']
other_categories = sorted([cat for cat in disability_data['disability_category'].unique() if cat != 'Any'])
category_order.extend(other_categories)

# Create the boxplot
ax = sns.boxplot(
    x='disability_category',
    y='prevalence_pct',
    data=disability_data,
    order=category_order,
    width=0.6,
    linewidth=1,
    legend=True
)

# Add a title and labels
plt.title('Distribution of Disability Prevalence by Type', fontsize=16, pad=20)
plt.ylabel('Prevalence (%)', fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Disability Type', fontsize=14)
plt.xticks(rotation=30, ha='right', fontsize=12)

# Add grid lines
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Customize y-axis limits
plt.ylim(0, max(disability_data['prevalence_pct']) * 1.1)

# Add mean markers
for i, disability in enumerate(category_order):
    mean_val = disability_data[disability_data['disability_category'] == disability]['prevalence_pct'].mean()
    y_pos = 18
    ax.text(i, y_pos, f'Mean: {mean_val:.1f}%', ha='center', va='top', fontsize=10)

plt.tight_layout()

We now have gone from 30+ columns to 11 essential columns, while preserving important information about confidence intervals. Now we can continue to explore this dataset.

Ranking Based on Cognitive Disability Percentage¶

Since different years are stored in different rows, we will sue only the 2022 data (most recent in the dataset). We can rank all 50 states based on percentage of cognitive disability.

In [ ]:
# Filter for cognitive disability type from the cleaned dataset
cognitive = dhds_clean[dhds_clean['disability_category'] == 'Cognitive']

most_recent_year = 2022

# Filter for just 2022
recent_cognitive = cognitive[cognitive['Year'] == most_recent_year]

# Sort states by prevalence rate (descending)
cognitive_by_state = recent_cognitive.sort_values('prevalence_pct', ascending=False)

# Assuming state codes for actual states are 2 letters
state_cognitive = cognitive_by_state[cognitive_by_state['state'].str.len() == 2]

# Show top 5 states with highest rates
print("\nStates with highest cognitive disability rates:")
result_table = state_cognitive[['state', 'prevalence_pct', 'ci_lower', 'ci_upper', 'sample_size']].head(5)

if 'state_names' in locals():
  result_table['State Name'] = result_table['state'].map(state_names)

# Rename columns
result_table = result_table.rename(columns={
    'state': 'State',
    'prevalence_pct': 'Prevalence (%)',
    'ci_lower': 'Lower CI',
    'ci_upper': 'Upper CI',
    'sample_size': 'Sample Size'
})

# Print table
print(result_table)

# Calculate the national average for 2022
us_data = cognitive[(cognitive['state'] == 'US') & (cognitive['Year'] == most_recent_year)]
if not us_data.empty:
    national_avg = us_data['prevalence_pct'].values[0]
    print(f"\nNational average cognitive disability prevalence: {national_avg:.1f}%")

Building Models¶

Logistic Regression for Tobacco Dataset¶

Now it's time to build our model! We want to examine the relationship between year and state and smoker characteristics. We have a few different options when we are trying to predict the smoker characteristics based on the year/state inputs.

We initially tried to use linear and polynomial regression, but we ran into a major problem: these models can predict values outside of our range (0-100%)! Obviously, we cannot have (for example) -4.7% of people who have never smoked, so we had to change strategies.

We decided to use a logistic regression on logit-transformed data with polynomial year terms for the following reasons:

  1. Linear regression models predict values anywhere from −∞ to +∞, which is problematic for percentages. By applying the logit transformation to percentages (rescaling from [0, 100] → [0, 1] → (−∞, +∞)), we can:
  • Fit a linear model on the log-odds scale (unbounded)
  • Then transform predictions back using the inverse logit, ensuring values stay in the [0, 1] range
  • Multiply by 100 to return to percentage scale
  1. We can capture nonlinear trends over time. The problem is that smoking trends are rarely perfectly linear, so adding year as a polynomial term adds for more realistic curvature.
  2. We can account for state-to-state differences. Clearly, different states have different cultural norms, laws, and demographics, which can vastly affect the smoking rates. For example, Kentucky has almost 3x the average smoking rate of Utah (as seen in our EDA), which is likely due to the large Mormon population in Utah, which drives their rates down.

We first need to define our logit and inverse logit functions

In [ ]:
# --- Helper functions for logit and inverse logit ---
def logit(p):
    p = np.clip(p, 1e-5, 1 - 1e-5)  # prevent log(0)
    return np.log(p / (1 - p))

def inv_logit(x):
    return 1 / (1 + np.exp(-x))

Next, we need to clean our data to ensure we can model on it, which includes removing NA values, converting our percentages to proportions, adding polynomial features, and encoding the state variable.

In [ ]:
# Remove any NA values
tobacco_clean = tobacco.dropna(subset=[
    'Year', 'State',
    'Smoke everyday', 'Smoke some days',
    'Former smoker', 'Never smoked'
])

# Convert target % columns to proportions
target_columns = ['Smoke everyday', 'Smoke some days', 'Former smoker', 'Never smoked']
for col in target_columns:
    tobacco_clean[col] = tobacco_clean[col] / 100

# Add polynomial features
tobacco_clean['Year2'] = tobacco_clean['Year'] ** 2

# OneHot encode 'State'
encoder = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore', sparse_output=False)
state_encoded = encoder.fit_transform(tobacco_clean[['State']])
state_columns = encoder.get_feature_names_out(['State'])

Now, we get to the modeling aspect. We build our model inputs and create our future prediction timeframe. Since the data ends at 2010, we start at 2011 and end with 2030 (a twenty-year timeframe).

In [ ]:
# Build model inputs
X_combined = pd.DataFrame(state_encoded, columns=state_columns)
X_combined['Year'] = tobacco_clean['Year'].values
X_combined['Year2'] = tobacco_clean['Year2'].values

# --- Create future prediction frame ---
future_years = list(range(2011, 2030))
# States to plot
plot_states = ['Alabama', 'Alaska', 'Arizona', 'Arkansas']
future_df = pd.DataFrame([(year, state) for state in plot_states for year in future_years],
                         columns=['Year', 'State'])
future_df['Year2'] = future_df['Year'] ** 2

future_encoded = encoder.transform(future_df[['State']])
future_X_combined = pd.DataFrame(future_encoded, columns=state_columns)
future_X_combined['Year'] = future_df['Year']
future_X_combined['Year2'] = future_df['Year2']

We then fit the model. We want to plot some of the predictions, but we don't want the plot to get too messy with over 50 different predictions, so we grab an arbitrary list of four to plot so we can get an idea of what the model is doing.

In [ ]:
# States to plot
plot_states = ['Alabama', 'Alaska', 'Arizona', 'Arkansas']

# --- Fit and predict ---
models = {}
future_predictions = future_df.copy()

for col in target_columns:
    # Apply logit transformation
    y_logit = logit(tobacco_clean[col].values)

    # Fit model on logit values
    model = LinearRegression()
    model.fit(X_combined, y_logit)
    models[col] = model

    # Predict and apply inverse logit
    y_pred_logit = model.predict(future_X_combined)
    y_pred = inv_logit(y_pred_logit) * 100  # convert back to %
    future_predictions[col] = y_pred

    # --- Plot ---
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    for state in plot_states:
        # Historical
        df_hist = tobacco_clean[tobacco_clean['State'] == state]
        plt.scatter(df_hist['Year'], df_hist[col] * 100, label=f"{state} (actual)", alpha=0.6)

        # Future
        df_pred = future_predictions[future_predictions['State'] == state]
        plt.plot(df_pred['Year'], df_pred[col], label=f"{state} (pred)", linestyle='--')

    plt.title(f"{col} - Logistic Regression (bounded 0–100%)")
    plt.xlabel("Year")
    plt.ylabel(f"{col} (%)")
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

Predicting Disability Status Based on Tobacco Usage¶

We now want to examine the relationship between tobacco usage and disability status in a single year. Since we're working with percentages (both disability prevalence and smoking rates are expressed as percentages), we need to be careful about our modeling approach.

We'll use a similar approach to the tobacco prediction model, applying a logistic transformation to ensure our predictions stay within the valid range of 0-100%.

We can reuse the same logit helper functions as in the previous section. First we will need to clean and prepare our datasets.

Further Resources¶

Our work is just the tip of the iceberg of potential explorations between smoking and disabilities. We could dive deeper into smoking rates within states, between demographics, or try to predict how individuals will smoke over their life duration. Similarly, we could improve our model that predicts disability rate based on state and smoking habits.

The CDC published this paper in 2014 that examined the disparities in cigarette smoking prevalence by type of disability from 2009-2011. The study used statistical analyses, including hypothesis tests and confidence intervals, but doesn't have any signficant modeling. They found that adults with a disability were more likely than adults without a disability to be current smokers. Furthermore, when controlling for sociodemographic characteristics, having a disability was associated with higher odds of current smoking. They concluded that the prevalence of current smoking for adults was higher for every functional disability type than for adults without a disability and that by understanding the association between smoking and disability type among adults younger than 50 years of age, resources for cessation services can be better targeted during the ages when increased time for health improvement can occur.

Another paper, written by reseachers from the University of Vermont, Indiana University, and Rutgers University, published in 2022, examined trends in cigarette smoking prevalence and status among U.S. adults with disabilities from 2015-2019. They also used statistical analyses, with both hypothesis tests and confidence intervals being used. They found that from 2015–2019, the overall prevalence of current cigarette smoking and the proportion of those with nicotine dependence was higher in people with any disability compared to those without. Additionally, the prevalence of current cigarette smoking decreased while the prevalence of former cigarette smoking increased from 2015 to 2019. People with any disability had higher odds of current smoking and similar odds of former smoking compared to people without disabilities.They concluded that the prevalence of cigarette smoking among people with any disability decreased over time but remained higher than those without. People with any disability had similar odds of former smoking, though differences existed by disability domain. Future research should explore additional smoking and quit behaviors by disability functioning domain.

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'qtpdf', 'qtpng', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
